	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nTwWeW98eyfROdh2K",
			"markdown": "You excel at dealing with people. Whether through charm, deception, diplomacy, intimidation, or sheer force of personality, you shape conversations and relationships to achieve your goals. In civilized societies, Faces are often more powerful than soldiers; they broker alliances, manipulate rivals, calm angry crowds, seduce patrons, negotiate treaties, and turn enemies into useful acquaintances. Even in rougher settings, a quick tongue and a sharp understanding of human nature can be worth more than a loaded gun.\n\nMany campaigns and societies have room for Faces, though exactly what form they take varies enormously. You might be a polished diplomat, a criminal fixer, a charismatic cult leader, a corporate negotiator, a celebrity performer, a smooth-talking rogue, or the public voice of an adventuring crew. Modern and futuristic societies often elevate Faces into positions of real influence: media celebrities, political operatives, propagandists, social influencers, lobbyists, negotiators, and corporate spokespeople can shape public opinion as effectively as soldiers shape battlefields. Most Faces specialize in a particular social approach, but the best can adapt to nearly any audience or situation.\n\nThe *Diplomat* is the ambassador, noble, negotiator, clergy member, or respected community leader who resolves conflict through tact, legitimacy, and persuasion. Diplomats thrive in courts, councils, summits, and ceremonial environments where status and etiquette matter as much as truth. They focus on negotiation, politics, etiquette, and leadership, emphasizing Diplomacy, Politics, Psychology, Public Speaking, Savoir-Faire, Cultural Adaptability, Empathy, and Leadership. Common disadvantages include Code of Honor, Sense of Duty, Honesty, Truthfulness, Charitable, or Pacifism (Reluctant Killer).\n\nThe *Grifter* survives through charm, lies, manipulation, and opportunism. Con artists, hustlers, smugglers, rogue traders, gamblers, and criminal intermediaries all fit this archetype. A Grifter succeeds by reading people quickly, adapting constantly, and convincing others to trust them just long enough to take advantage. They focus on Fast-Talk, Acting, Gambling, Merchant, Streetwise, Detect Lies, Sex Appeal, Rapier Wit, Honest Face, and Smooth Operator. Their lifestyle often encourages disadvantages such as Greed, Compulsive Lying, Trickster, Overconfidence, Jealousy, or Social Stigma (Criminal Record).\n\nThe *Performer* commands attention through art, entertainment, spectacle, or public charisma. This archetype includes entertainers, celebrities, propagandists, revolutionary speakers, court bards, influencers, charismatic religious figures, and media personalities. Performers shape emotions and public opinion as much through presence as through argument, often becoming cultural icons or symbols larger than themselves. They emphasize Singing, Acting, Public Speaking, Musical Instrument, Performance, Fashion Sense, Born Entertainer, Charisma, and Cultural Chameleon. Common disadvantages include Compulsive Carousing, Chummy or Gregarious, Selfish, or Code of Honor (Theatrical).\n\nThe *Fixer* thrives on connections, favors, leverage, and information networks. Political aides, underworld brokers, corporate negotiators, intelligence liaisons, talent agents, and organized-crime intermediaries all fall under this archetype. A good Fixer survives not because they are the strongest or smartest person in the room, but because they always know someone who owes them a favor. They focus on Streetwise, Merchant, Politics, Leadership, Psychology, Detect Lies, Savoir-Faire, Contacts, and Smooth Operator. Typical disadvantages include Workaholic, Greed, Sense of Duty, Secret, Selfish, or Overconfidence.\n\nA major decision is whether your Face relies primarily on honesty, manipulation, or sheer charisma. A truthful diplomat and a professional con artist may possess many of the same skills, but they solve problems in very different ways. Likewise, some Faces cultivate universal appeal through Cultural Adaptability and languages, while others dominate a narrow social environment such as the criminal underworld, high society, military circles, or mass media. Consider carefully which audiences your character understands best, and which situations leave them out of their depth.\n\nMost Faces benefit enormously from broad secondary skills. Background talents such as Connoisseur, Heraldry, Makeup, Writing, Administration, Observation, Games, or Electronics Operation (Media) help define how your character operates socially. Even combat skills matter: a Face rarely wins fights through force, but a little training in pistols, boxing, or knife can be invaluable when negotiations fail."
		}
